🇺🇦 Meet the Lieman's from Ukraine. Olha, Anton, and Mariia (9) and their cat (Bars!) will be arriving in Texas shortly having narrowly escaped the war. The US allows Americans to act as private sponsors for Ukrainians to live and work here, my family will be acting as the Liemans sponsors. Through an organization @welcome.us , we met the Lieman's and will be responsible for supporting their transition. Like many displaced people, their story is one of resilience. In the face of astonishing obstacles, we have found the Lieman's to be resilient, optimistic, and devoted. They’ve fled the war not once, but twice. As their sponsors, we're launching a fundraiser to help cover their initial costs of settling in before they find jobs.Every contribution will monumentally change the course of the Lieman's lives. Please consider donating - GoFundMe link in bio and with their full story. 🙏🏽 #unitingforukraine🇺🇸🇺🇦 #unitingforukraineспонсор

Lockhart Murals! Swipe for full story: 
THE BOARD: The Lockhart Historic Board is an important part of the community who's purpose is to preserve the downtown historical buildings. They have done amazing things to keep Lockhart's downtown in beautiful shape, while holding its historic character, one of the many reasons residents and tourists enjoy this town.
THE MURAL: In November, @texasmonthly sponsored this mural on the square for the Texas Monthly BBQ Festival that will now be an annual event, bringing tourists state and nationwide, helping our town thrive and represent what Lockhart is best known for...BBQ!
THE SCOOP: The Lockhart Historic Board disagrees and wants to paint over this mural and potentially not allow future murals. If you (respectfully) disagree with the board on this issue, there is a meeting on Wednesday, February 15th at 5:30pm (PROMPT) in the basement of city hall. If you think this mural is a great addition to the community, then come to the meeting this Wednesday. Let's also be reminded of the board's continued work to preserve the historic downtown and integrity of the buildings, while we can respectfully disagree on this particular issue. We are still a community.

A year ago today I lost my sweet friend, Edith at the age of 102. I was on my way to DC for her birthday and we just didn’t make it in time. Edith was a friend of mine in DC I would have dinner with every Sunday night for nearly a decade. She was from Germany and her and her husband escaped the war after concentration camp. She never had children, I didn’t really have grandparents, so we adopted each other. My last conversation with her was the night before she passed and I told her our daughter that I was pregnant with would have Edith as her middle name. I barely missed her to say goodbye in person, and that week in DC we ended up cleaning out her apartment. So many photos and memories, and treasures I got to bring back to remember her by. My sweet Edith 🫶🏼

🌟 Favorite 2023 Vintage Trends: Percival Lafer🌟 

Percival Lafer is an iconic Brazilian designer known for starting the Brazilian modernist movement.

3 FACTS:

1. Mid-century modern, but plush: While American and European mid-century modern furniture is streamlined, Lafer’s designs are plusher - using thicker, more comfortable padding and warm Brazilian rosewood.
2. Furniture that appreciates in value: Despite his goal of modern design at affordable prices, Percival’s vintage furniture designs are gaining more and more value as he’s been rediscovered in 2023.
3. More than just a furniture designer: In 1970’s, Lafer designed the fiberglass-bodied MP Lafer Sports Car featured in the Bond movie Moonraker.

HOW TO STYLE PERCIVAL LAFER VINTAGE FURNITURE:
- Mid-century Magic: Slides easily into any mid-century modern aesthetic.
- Keep it Simple: Keep the surrounding elements simple and minimal to make the Percival sofa your anchor statement piece
- Perfect for plant parents: Percival’s are very natural-inspired designs and use organic elements like Brazilian rosewood, they are ideal next to plant heavy rooms.

Percival Lafer Pieces: The MP-041 series (1965), MP-89 Armchair (1970) the MP-071 Armchair (1973); the S1 Collection (1975), the MP-163 Armchair (1976), better known as the “Earth Chair”, the MP-81, MP-211

This weekend while my family and I were visiting relatives, someone threw a large rock through the Stampworthy storefront window. It left quite a massive hole, causing us to board up the window.

While this was such a disappointing call to receive, I have been blown away by our sweet small town and how they showed up this weekend. Sweet Caroline @caroline_in_the_county called me as soon as she saw it, making herself available to find a solution, called our shop pal Stevan @alcala73 and he was boarding up the window literally before I knew it. The Lockhart police department @lockhartlpa showed up immediately and the Historic Board president personally walked the block this weekend while I was away to keep an eye on the shop.

While it was a disheartening thing to come home to, I am so grateful for our sweet town and community. Shop drop delayed unitl tomorrow.

Emeco + Stark 100% Recycled Chairs ♻️ - perfect for indoor or outdoor use. 12 available 

The Broom chair is made of a new composite of discarded industrial materials, reclaimed even before they enter the long waste-cycle that most recycled materials have to undergo today. By reclaiming the waste in its purest form they save natural resources and reduce energy at the same time. Emeco and Philippe Starck have together created a new chair that literally sweeps up the waste from the industrial manufacturing cycle.
The Broom chair is made of 75% reclaimed polypropylene, 15% reclaimed wood fibers and 10% glass fiber & pigment. Reclaimed polypropylene is an industrial waste material from plastic production, while the reclaimed wood fiber is left over from lumber manufacture. The two materials are combined to create a wood-polypropylene composite called WPP. This is then injected with gas during the molding process, creating a hollow yet incredibly strong structure.

By using reclaimed waste instead of raw materials they reduce waste and use less energy. So the Broom chair is made with a minimal impact on the environment: it’s reclaimed, repurposed and recyclable- and it’s also designed to last.

STAR TREK UNICORN SWIVEL CHAIRS BY CHROMCRAFT 

In a collaboration with Vladimir Kagan, Chromcraft created the Sculpta futuristic chairs. The aluminum “V” base lends itself to the “unicorn” nickname. It gives the chair the appearance of movement—a sort of pushing forward into the future—which is why it was so appealing to the set designers of the original “Star Trek” television show.
Featured in a few episodes, including one of the most famous (“The Trouble with Tribbles”), the chair fits in perfectly with the space-age aesthetic. “Star Trek’s” use of this chair helped propel the Chromcraft brand into a household name.
